</node>
<node id="&quot;NATURAL HARMONIC SERIES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Natural Harmonic Series is the sequence of tones that occur naturally when a string or air column is vibrated at different frequencies."&lt;SEP&gt;"The natural harmonic series is a sequence of frequencies that are integer multiples of a fundamental frequency, often used in music and vocal techniques."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;G2&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"G2 is a specific note in the natural harmonic series, typically the second harmonic of a fundamental frequency."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ROCK&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Rock is a genre of music that often uses inharmonic overtones, which are not part of the standard numerical sequence of harmonics."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BLUES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Blues is a genre of music that often uses inharmonic overtones, which are not part of the standard numerical sequence of harmonics."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;INHARMONIC OVERTONES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Inharmonic overtones are sounds that are not part of the standard numerical sequence of harmonics and are commonly found in rock and blues music, as well as in voices with damaged or pathological conditions."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VOCAL TRACTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Vocal tracts are the physical structures in the human body used for producing speech sounds, and they can be tuned to highlight specific harmonics in the harmonic series."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TUVA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Tuva is a region known for throat singing or overtone singing, a vocal technique that involves highlighting specific harmonics within the harmonic spectrum."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;THROAT SINGING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Throat singing or overtone singing is a vocal technique found in regions like Tuva, where singers tune their vocal tracts to highlight specific harmonics, creating a melody within the natural harmonic series."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;OVERTONE SINGING&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Overtone singing is a vocal technique similar to throat singing, found in regions like Tuva, where singers highlight specific harmonics within the harmonic spectrum to create a melody."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LOW-PITCHED DRONE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Low-Pitched Drone is a sustained note that forms the base of the melody created by singers."&lt;SEP&gt;"Low-pitched drones are sustained notes produced by throat singers as a base for creating melodies using specific harmonics within the natural harmonic series."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;COMFORTABLE PITCH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Comfortable Pitch is a note within the singer's vocal range that is easy to sustain."&lt;SEP&gt;"Comfortable pitches are notes within a singer's range that can be sustained without strain, often used as a base for creating melodies using specific harmonics within the natural harmonic series."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-18b5be2df8e19f7884cf7a5899385ca9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SINGERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Singers refer to individuals who perform using the technique of sustaining a low-pitched drone and creating melodies by moving between tones within the natural harmonic series."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VOCAL FOLD VIBRATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Vocal Fold Vibration refers to the mode of vibration of the vocal folds, which impacts the overtones produced and thus the sound quality."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MODE 1&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mode 1 is a vocal fold vibration mode characterized by relatively strong high-frequency harmonics, resulting in a brighter, brassier sound."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;MODE 2&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Mode 2 is a vocal fold vibration mode characterized by much weaker high-frequency harmonics, resulting in a less bright sound."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VOCAL TRACT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The vocal tract is the pathway through which sound travels in the production of speech, involving various parts such as the tongue, lips, jaw, palate, and larynx."&lt;SEP&gt;"Vocal Tract is the hollow space within the body used for producing speech sounds, consisting of the pharynx, oral cavity, and nasal cavity."&lt;SEP&gt;"Vocal Tract is the source of resonance in the human body, responsible for amplifying and enhancing the sound through supplemental vibration."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-19cc232c450902b9e868c6fdfd3aa6b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;RESONANCE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Resonance is the amplification and enhancement of musical sound through supplemental vibration, making instruments louder and more beautiful by reinforcing the original vibrations of the sound source."&lt;SEP&gt;"Resonance is the phenomenon of sound waves reinforcing each other."&lt;SEP&gt;"Resonance is the phenomenon where the vocal tract and sound source synchronize, resulting in a significant increase in sound intensity."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-19cc232c450902b9e868c6fdfd3aa6b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUPPLEMENTAL VIBRATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Supplemental Vibration is the process by which resonance enhances the original vibrations of the sound source, making the sound louder and more beautiful."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SOUNDBOARD&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Soundboard is a component of musical instruments that amplifies the vibrations of the strings."&lt;SEP&gt;"Soundboard is a component of musical instruments, specifically pianos, that transmits vibrations from the strings to amplify sound."&lt;SEP&gt;"Soundboard is the resonator in pianos, amplifying the vibrations of the strings and transmitting them to the air."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BRIDGE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Bridge is a component of musical instruments that transmits the vibrations of the strings to the soundboard."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bridge is a component of musical instruments, such as violins and guitars, that transmits vibrations from the strings to the soundboard."&lt;SEP&gt;"Bridge is a structure found in pianos, violins, and guitars that transmits the vibrations of the strings to the soundboard."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WHISTLE-LIKE TONE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Whistle-like Tone refers to a specific type of sound used by singers to create a melody within the natural harmonic series."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TONES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Tones are individual notes or frequencies used by singers to create a melody."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HIGH-FREQUENCY HARMONICS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"High-Frequency Harmonics are the higher tones produced by the vocal folds in Mode 1, contributing to a brighter sound."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BRIGHTER SOUND&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Brighter Sound is the result of strong high-frequency harmonics in Mode 1, giving the sound a brassier quality."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LESS BRIGHT SOUND&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Less Bright Sound is the result of weaker high-frequency harmonics in Mode 2, giving the sound a softer quality."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;AMPLIFICATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Amplification is a technology that was introduced to theater stages in the late 1920s and 1930s, improving the audibility of singers."&lt;SEP&gt;"Amplification is the process by which resonance increases the volume and clarity of the sound."&lt;SEP&gt;"Amplification is the process of increasing the volume of sound, which mix/belt singing aims to avoid in the middle register."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f78a750cb7a4af5093bc7229882bc6f0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-026ac83dff25b4f662d33b415113ce9e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ENHANCEMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Enhancement is the process by which resonance enriches the sound, making it more pleasing to the ear."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;INSTRUMENTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Instruments are objects that produce sound and can be amplified and enhanced through resonance."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PIANO&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Piano is a musical instrument that uses strings and a soundboard to produce sound."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VIOLIN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Violin is a musical instrument that uses strings and a soundboard to produce sound."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;GUITAR&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Guitar is a musical instrument that uses strings and a soundboard to produce sound."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;STRINGS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Strings are the components that vibrate to produce sound in musical instruments."&lt;SEP&gt;"Strings are the vibrating parts of musical instruments that produce sound when plucked, strummed, or bowed."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FREE RESONANCE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Free Resonance is a phenomenon where sound travels through a hollow space, such as the vocal tract, creating a complex pattern of echoes that can enhance the quality of sound."&lt;SEP&gt;"Free Resonance is the process by which resonance occurs without physical connection to a vibrator."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FORCED RESONANCE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Forced Resonance is a phenomenon where vibrations are transmitted through a medium, such as the chest during speech, creating a sensation that can impact self-perception but is not audible to others."&lt;SEP&gt;"Forced Resonance is the process by which resonance occurs through physical connection to a vibrator."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VIBRATIONS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Vibrations are the oscillations of particles in a medium, producing sound waves."&lt;SEP&gt;"Vibrations refer to the physical oscillations that occur in the strings of musical instruments and in the vocal folds during speech and singing."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;AIR COLUMN&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Air Column is a length of air that can be vibrated to produce sound, such as in a flute or organ pipe."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-16d39b19193e67d1a3c47d1a2851f964</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;GLOTTIS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Glottis is the opening in the larynx where the vocal folds are located, essential for producing sound."&lt;SEP&gt;"Glottis is the opening in the larynx where the vocal folds are located, responsible for producing sound in the vocal cords."&lt;SEP&gt;"The glottis is the opening in the larynx through which air passes during breathing and through which sound is produced during phonation."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-19cc232c450902b9e868c6fdfd3aa6b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BOARD&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Board is a component of musical instruments, specifically pianos, that transmits vibrations from the strings to amplify sound."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;THICK LAYER OF FOAM RUBBER&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Thick Layer of Foam Rubber is a hypothetical material used to dampen vibrations."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHARYNX&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pharynx is the throat part of the vocal tract."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ORGAN PIPE&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Organ Pipe is a hollow tube used in wind instruments to produce sound."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;TRUMPET&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Trumpet is a brass wind instrument."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CANYON&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"GEO"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A canyon is a deep valley with steep sides, often carved by a river, which is used as an analogy for the reflection of sound waves."&lt;SEP&gt;"Canyon is an analogy used to describe the reflection of sound waves."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-19cc232c450902b9e868c6fdfd3aa6b0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PULSE OF SOUND&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pulse of Sound is the periodic emission of sound waves."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-0693f03528085d6f9c9b9a9f1da30c13</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SOUND&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Sound is the physical vibration that travels through the vocal tract and can be manipulated to produce speech or other sounds."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-19cc232c450902b9e868c6fdfd3aa6b0</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FORMANTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Formants are the resonant frequencies or areas in which strong amplification occurs in the vocal tract."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-19cc232c450902b9e868c6fdfd3aa6b0</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EXPENSE REIMBURSEMENT AMOUNT&quot;">
