<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER&quot;" target="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Pantomime is a subset of Music Theater, specifically a form of storytelling within the broader genre."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER&quot;" target="&quot;ARTISTIC DEVELOPMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Artistic Development refers to the period of growth and innovation in the music theater genre during the 1920s."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER&quot;" target="&quot;AMERICAN MUSICAL THEATER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Music theater is a form of theatrical performance that combines songs, spoken dialogue, acting, and dance, evolving from various European ancestral forms and incorporating modern styles."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-289a23908915c5bcd0308dffe4b44213</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;MOTHER GOOSE STORIES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Mother Goose Stories provide the basis for the characters in American pantomime performances."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;ITALIAN COMMEDIA DELL' ARTE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Italian Commedia dell' Arte influenced American pantomime by transforming Mother Goose characters into clown figures."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;CLOWNS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Clowns are performers in pantomime who use silent gestures to convey mostly comedic stories."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;IMMIGRANTS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Immigrants benefited from the visual storytelling of pantomime due to their limited understanding of spoken English."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;BURLESQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Burlesque was a form of entertainment that existed before the rise of musical comedy and was more intimate than pantomime."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;MUSICAL COMEDY&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Musical Comedy emerged after the decline of pantomime, offering a more intimate style than burlesque and a less childish experience than pantomime."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;LONDON&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Pantomime acts were performed in London in the 1700s on the stages there."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;CHILDISHNESS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Childishness is a characteristic of pantomime that was less childish than musical comedy."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;VISUAL STORYTELLING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Visual Storytelling is a method of conveying stories through body or facial movements, which was a key aspect of pantomime."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;COMEDY&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Comedy is a genre of storytelling that includes mostly comedic stories conveyed through silent gestures in pantomime."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;EXCITEMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Excitement is a factor that increased audience engagement in pantomime performances through the use of silent gestures and occasional singing by clowns."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;ENGLISH LANGUAGE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"English Language is the primary language spoken by the majority of the audience, but some were immigrants who spoke little English, benefiting from the visual storytelling of pantomime."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PANTOMIME&quot;" target="&quot;1735–1864&quot;">
  <data key="d4">3.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The period from 1735 to 1864 saw the emergence of forms like pantomime, which influenced the development of American musical theater."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-289a23908915c5bcd0308dffe4b44213</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BURLESQUE&quot;" target="&quot;INTIMACY&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Intimacy is a characteristic of burlesque that was more intimate than pantomime."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BURLESQUE&quot;" target="&quot;AMERICAN MUSICAL THEATER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">2.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Burlesque influenced American musical theater with its comedic and sometimes risqué elements."&lt;</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-289a23908915c5bcd0308dffe4b44213</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSICAL COMEDY&quot;" target="&quot;INTIMACY&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Intimacy is a characteristic of musical comedy that was more intimate than burlesque."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;1920S&quot;" target="&quot;ARTISTIC DEVELOPMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The 1920s saw remarkable artistic development in the music theater genre."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;1920S&quot;" target="&quot;GOLDEN AGE OF BROADWAY&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The 1920s is the period during which the Golden Age of Broadway began in 1925."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-d7778c1993fee70b814ec6d95d5a65fa</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;50 NEW MUSIC THEATER PRODUCTIONS&quot;" target="&quot;ARTISTIC DEVELOPMENT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Some seasons introduced as many as fifty new music theater productions during the busiest decade of Broadway's music theater genre."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-41335195b13ad0268bb37014c08227ef</data>
