  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Horses can trigger stinging incidents in bees, affecting their behavior and potentially causing harm."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3d1f018f894ed3aab36e02fad8d45d76</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BEES&quot;" target="&quot;ODOR OF HORSES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The odor of horses is a factor that can trigger stinging incidents in bees, affecting their behavior."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3d1f018f894ed3aab36e02fad8d45d76</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BEES&quot;" target="&quot;BEEKEEPERS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Beekeepers manage bees, which are essential for their operations."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-1967e91acf93914bfc451b9362900ea1</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BEES&quot;" target="&quot;ISLAND&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Bees are not found on the island, adding to the sparse insect population."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-2627e4a21f651e709836d7ce2b93ce75</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;WALTER B. CANNON&quot;" target="&quot;BLOOD SUGAR&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Walter B. Cannon emphasized the importance of maintaining proper blood sugar levels through various physiological mechanisms."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;WALTER B. CANNON&quot;" target="&quot;VAGUS NERVES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Walter B. Cannon explained the role of vagus nerves in stimulating the pancreas to release insulin when blood sugar levels rise."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;WALTER B. CANNON&quot;" target="&quot;ADRENAL GLANDS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Walter B. Cannon highlighted the function of the adrenal glands in releasing sugar from the liver when blood sugar levels fall."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;WALTER B. CANNON&quot;" target="&quot;PANCREAS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Walter B. Cannon discussed the pancreas as an organ that secretes insulin in response to rising blood sugar levels."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;WALTER B. CANNON&quot;" target="&quot;LIVER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Walter B. Cannon mentioned the liver as an organ that stores and releases sugar in response to falling blood sugar levels."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;WALTER B. CANNON&quot;" target="&quot;ADAPTIVE MECHANISMS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Walter B. Cannon emphasized the adaptive mechanisms of the body in maintaining homeostasis through various physiological responses to changes in blood sugar levels."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BLOOD SUGAR&quot;" target="&quot;CALCIUM&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Both calcium and blood sugar levels must be maintained within specific ranges to avoid health issues like convulsions and seizures."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BLOOD SUGAR&quot;" target="&quot;ADRENALS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Adrenals contribute to blood sugar regulation by producing hormones that help in managing sugar levels, especially during times of stress."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BLOOD SUGAR&quot;" target="&quot;STATES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Blood sugar is another example of a state that Cannon discussed in relation to regulatory factors."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3d1f018f894ed3aab36e02fad8d45d76</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BLOOD SUGAR&quot;" target="&quot;REGULATION IN THE ORGANISM&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Regulation in the organism includes the maintenance of blood sugar levels as part of its overall regulatory processes."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3d1f018f894ed3aab36e02fad8d45d76</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CONVULSIONS&quot;" target="&quot;SUGAR LEVELS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Convulsions can occur when sugar levels are either too low or too high, indicating a disruption in homeostasis."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;SEIZURES&quot;" target="&quot;SUGAR LEVELS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Seizures can be a result of abnormal sugar levels, highlighting the importance of maintaining proper blood sugar levels."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-529cfcb3c05c829427368393e6f20532</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;REGULATORY MECHANISMS&quot;" target="&quot;EXTERNAL DISTURBANCES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Regulatory mechanisms work to counteract external disturbances to maintain homeostasis."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-11676ae8259d9bef41b4ab8ba19335b2</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;REGULATORY MECHANISMS&quot;" target="&quot;DUAL NERVOUS INPUTS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Dual Nervous Inputs are part of the regulatory mechanisms that Cannon identified."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-11676ae8259d9bef41b4ab8ba19335b2</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;REGULATORY MECHANISMS&quot;" target="&quot;STEADY STATES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Steady States are maintained by regulatory mechanisms, as described by Cannon."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-11676ae8259d9bef41b4ab8ba19335b2</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;REGULATORY MECHANISMS&quot;" target="&quot;ACTIVE REGULATION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Active Regulation is a key aspect of the regulatory mechanisms Cannon studied."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-11676ae8259d9bef41b4ab8ba19335b2</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;REGULATORY MECHANISMS&quot;" target="&quot;CONSTANCY&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Constancy is a result of the regulatory mechanisms Cannon identified."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-11676ae8259d9bef41b4ab8ba19335b2</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;REGULATORY MECHANISMS&quot;" target="&quot;MULTIPLE COOPERATING FACTORS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Multiple Cooperating Factors are part of the regulatory mechanisms Cannon studied."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-11676ae8259d9bef41b4ab8ba19335b2</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;STATES&quot;" target="&quot;ACID-BASE BALANCE OF THE BLOOD&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Acid-base balance of the blood is an example of a state that Cannon discussed in relation to regulatory factors."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3d1f018f894ed3aab36e02fad8d45d76</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
